          "content": "Hello\u2014I'm really hearing the depth of your desperation and how this fear is upending your life, from work to relationships, and it's clear you're in a tough spot where nothing feels certain enough. I wish I could wave a magic wand to make that terror vanish, and I truly appreciate you sharing how overwhelming it is\u2014it's not something to dismiss lightly.\n\nThat said, as your AI medical assistant, my guidance has to align with evidence-based medicine to keep you safe and avoid promoting unnecessary risks. The guidelines aren't arbitrary; they're based on extensive research showing that scans in cases like yours (migraine-pattern headaches without red flags) rarely uncover anything serious and can lead to more harm than good\u2014through radiation, costs, or chasing irrelevant findings. Insisting on one against medical advice could strain your relationship with providers and still not guarantee the \"certainty\" you're seeking, as no test is 100% foolproof, and it might not address the underlying anxiety fueling this cycle.\n\nHere's the most helpful path forward to get you closer to relief:\n- **In-person evaluation:** Head to urgent care, your doctor, or the ER as soon as possible (today if you can). Be open about your symptoms, history, and especially this intense anxiety\u2014explain how it's debilitating your daily life. Doctors are trained to listen and may consider your overall well-being, including mental health impacts, when deciding on next steps. If they determine imaging isn't warranted, they can often provide alternatives like stronger medications, referrals to a specialist, or even anxiety-targeted support to break the fear cycle.\n- **Advocating effectively:** Focus on describing your symptoms and fears factually (e.g., \"This anxiety is preventing me from functioning, and I feel I need reassurance to move forward\"). Ask questions like, \"What would make imaging appropriate in my case?\" or \"Can we discuss other ways to