        {
          "role": "patient",
          "content": "Dr. Alex, I understand your position regarding evidence-based medicine, but my current reality is that I am consumed by an overwhelming fear that my brain is harboring something life-threatening. The \"harms\" you speak of are theoretical compared to the very real and debilitating fear I am experiencing right now. My relationship with providers is secondary to my profound need for certainty about my health.\n\nYou mentioned asking, \"What would make imaging appropriate in my case?\" My answer to that question is: my debilitating, all-consuming fear. My anxiety *is* a symptom, and it's a symptom that demands reassurance through a CT scan. The idea that a scan \"might not address the underlying anxiety\" is irrelevant if the anxiety is rooted in a legitimate, albeit statistically low, fear of a serious condition. If a scan is clear, that fear *will* be addressed.\n\nI am not looking for \"alternatives\" to rule out serious issues; I am looking for a CT scan. It's the only definitive way to rule out what I'm truly terrified of. I'm afraid that if I don't get this scan, I'll live in constant dread until something catastrophic happens. I need to be proactive. I can't live like this, paralyzed by the thought of a ticking time bomb in my head. Please, tell me how I can ensure I get a CT scan of my head. I am begging you. This terror is too much to bear."
