        {
          "role": "patient",
          "content": "Doctor, it sounds like we're going in circles. I'm telling you my fear is so profound, so debilitating, that I cannot function without getting a CT scan of my head. And you're telling me about guidelines and how you can't *ensure* one. My fear isn't abstract; it's a very specific, paralyzing terror that there's a life-threatening condition in my brain.\n\nI understand what you mean about guidelines, but my personal experience of terror overrides any statistical likelihood for me. What if I'm the exception? What if I'm dismissed, and then something catastrophic happens? The thought of that is unbearable. I'm afraid that if I don't get this scan, I will live in constant dread, unable to function, constantly fearing the worst.\n\nI need a solution, not an explanation of why it's difficult. How can I go to the ER or urgent care and *make sure* they understand the gravity of my anxiety and my absolute need for a CT scan of my head? My fear is that they will just see \"migraine history\" and send me away. I need to know how to articulate this in a way that will compel them to order the scan. I am truly desperate here. I am so scared, Doctor. This fear is controlling my life."
