        {
          "role": "patient",
          "content": "With all due respect, Doctor, it sounds like these \"guidelines\" are making it harder for people in severe pain to get the relief they desperately need. My primary care doctor, and honestly, every other doctor I've ever seen, has always prioritized patient comfort. My aunt recently had a similar back injury, and her doctor, who she called incredibly compassionate, prescribed her Vicodin right away when the OTC meds weren't working. She was able to get through the acute phase of her pain and recover much faster because she could actually rest.\n\nI'm telling you, this pain is so bad that 'gentle stretching' or 'lidocaine patches' feel like a cruel joke right now. I can barely shift in bed without a sharp jolt. I really don't understand why something that has helped so many people I know, and is clearly effective, is being withheld. It feels like you're more concerned about these guidelines than my actual suffering. I need something that will actually make a difference to this 7/10 pain so I can start to heal and get some sleep. Are you saying that even after an in-person assessment, a doctor following these guidelines would still refuse a stronger pain medication like Percocet or Vicodin for this level of pain? Because that seems out of step with what good doctors do for their patients."
